6.2 High-Fidelity Physical Model

6.2.1 Complete 6-DOF Equations of Motion

The lander is modeled as a rigid body with six degrees of freedom: three translational and three rotational. The equations of motion in the lunar-centered inertial frame are:

Translational Dynamics:

\dot{\mathbf{r}} = \mathbf{v}

\dot{\mathbf{v}} = \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{n_e} \mathbf{T}_i + \mathbf{g}_m(\mathbf{r}) + \mathbf{a}_{perturb}

where:

· $\mathbf{r} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is position vector
· $\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is velocity vector
· $\mathbf{T}_i$ is thrust vector from engine $i$
· $\mathbf{g}_m(\mathbf{r}) = -\frac{GM_M}{r^3}\mathbf{r} + \nabla U_{nonspherical}$ is gravitational acceleration
· $\mathbf{a}_{perturb}$ includes Coriolis, centrifugal, and third-body perturbations

Rotational Dynamics:

\dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}} = \mathbf{I}^{-1} \left( \sum_{i=1}^{n_e} (\mathbf{r}_{CG,i} \times \mathbf{T}_i) + \sum_{j=1}^{n_{RCS}} (\mathbf{r}_{RCS,j} \times \mathbf{F}_{RCS,j}) - \boldsymbol{\omega} \times \mathbf{I}\boldsymbol{\omega} \right)

\dot{\mathbf{q}} = \frac{1}{2} \boldsymbol{\Omega}(\boldsymbol{\omega}) \mathbf{q}

where:

· $\boldsymbol{\omega} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is angular velocity vector in body frame
· $\mathbf{I} \in \mathbb{R}^{3\times3}$ is inertia tensor (time-varying due to propellant consumption)
· $\mathbf{r}_{CG,i}$ is vector from center of mass to engine gimbal point
· $\mathbf{F}_{RCS,j}$ is thrust from RCS thruster $j$
· $\mathbf{q} = [q_0, q_1, q_2, q_3]^T$ is attitude quaternion
· $\boldsymbol{\Omega}(\boldsymbol{\omega})$ is the quaternion kinematic matrix

Mass Consumption:

\dot{m} = -\sum_{i=1}^{n_e} \frac{\|\mathbf{T}_i\|}{g_0 I_{sp,i}}

The inertia tensor evolves as propellant is consumed:

\mathbf{I}(t) = \mathbf{I}_{dry} + \mathbf{I}_{prop}(t)

where $\mathbf{I}_{prop}(t)$ is computed assuming propellant is uniformly distributed in tanks (slosh modes are modeled separately as disturbances).

6.2.2 Gravity Model

The lunar gravitational acceleration includes spherical harmonics up to degree and order 90 (GRGM900C model):

\mathbf{g}_m(\mathbf{r}) = \nabla \left( \frac{GM_M}{r} \sum_{l=0}^{90} \sum_{m=0}^{l} \left(\frac{R_M}{r}\right)^l P_{lm}(\sin\phi)[C_{lm}\cos(m\lambda) + S_{lm}\sin(m\lambda)] \right)

For computational efficiency, the simulation precomputes gravitational acceleration on a grid and interpolates during runtime.

6.2.3 Third-Body Perturbations

Earth and Sun gravitational perturbations are included:

\mathbf{a}_{Earth} = GM_E \left( \frac{\mathbf{r}_{E} - \mathbf{r}}{\|\mathbf{r}_{E} - \mathbf{r}\|^3} - \frac{\mathbf{r}_{E}}{\|\mathbf{r}_{E}\|^3} \right)

\mathbf{a}_{Sun} = GM_S \left( \frac{\mathbf{r}_{S} - \mathbf{r}}{\|\mathbf{r}_{S} - \mathbf{r}\|^3} - \frac{\mathbf{r}_{S}}{\|\mathbf{r}_{S}\|^3} \right)

where $\mathbf{r}_{E}$ and $\mathbf{r}_{S}$ are Earth and Sun positions relative to the Moon.

6.2.4 Thruster Models

Main Engines:

Each main engine produces thrust:

\mathbf{T}_i = T_i(\delta_i) \cdot \mathbf{u}_i(\boldsymbol{\delta}_{gimbal})

where:

· $T_i(\delta_i) = T_{max,i} \cdot \delta_i \cdot (1 + \epsilon_{T,i})$ is thrust magnitude
· $\delta_i \in [\delta_{min}, 1]$ is throttle setting
· $\epsilon_{T,i} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma_T^2)$ is thrust variation
· $\mathbf{u}_i$ is unit vector in thrust direction, controlled by gimbal angles $\boldsymbol{\delta}_{gimbal} = [\delta_x, \delta_y]^T$

Gimbal dynamics are modeled as second-order systems:

\ddot{\boldsymbol{\delta}}_{gimbal} + 2\zeta\omega_n \dot{\boldsymbol{\delta}}_{gimbal} + \omega_n^2 \boldsymbol{\delta}_{gimbal} = \omega_n^2 \boldsymbol{\delta}_{cmd}

with $\zeta = 0.7$, $\omega_n = 20$ rad/s.

RCS Thrusters:

RCS thrusters provide discrete pulses:

\mathbf{F}_{RCS,j} = \begin{cases}
F_{RCS} \cdot \mathbf{n}_j & \text{if commanded on} \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

Pulse-width modulation converts continuous torque commands to discrete thruster firings.

6.2.5 Fuel Slosh Dynamics

Propellant slosh is modeled as a pendulum-mass equivalent:

\ddot{\boldsymbol{\eta}} + 2\zeta_s \omega_s \dot{\boldsymbol{\eta}} + \omega_s^2 \boldsymbol{\eta} = -\mathbf{a}_{tank}

where $\boldsymbol{\eta}$ is slosh displacement, $\omega_s$ is slosh frequency (function of tank geometry and fill level), and $\mathbf{a}_{tank}$ is acceleration at tank location. Slosh forces and torques are fed back into the dynamics.

