6.7 Plume-Surface Interaction Modeling

6.7.1 PSI Physics Background

Plume-surface interaction occurs when rocket exhaust impinges on the lunar regolith. The high-velocity exhaust causes:

1. Cratering: Erosion of regolith beneath the engine
2. Ejecta: Lofted particles that can damage the vehicle
3. Obscuration: Dust clouds that degrade sensors
4. Thermal effects: Heating of surface and vehicle components

The physics is governed by the balance between aerodynamic shear stress at the surface and soil cohesion:

\tau_{shear} = \frac{1}{2} \rho_{plume} v_{plume}^2 C_f > \tau_{soil}

where $\tau_{soil}$ is soil shear strength.

6.7.2 Scaling Law Derivation

The crater depth scales with thrust and burn time. From dimensional analysis:

h_{crater} \propto \left( \frac{T}{p_{strength}} \right)^{a} \left( \frac{t_{burn}}{t_{ref}} \right)^{b} \left(1 + \frac{p_e}{p_{ref}}\right)

The exponents $a$ and $b$ are determined from CFD simulations and vacuum chamber tests. For the Langley 2026 dataset, the best-fit exponents are $a = 0.45$, $b = 0.6$.

The complete scaling law is:

h_{crater} = k \left( \frac{T/A_{ref}}{p_{strength}} \right)^{0.45} \left( \frac{t_{burn}}{t_{ref}} \right)^{0.6} \left(1 + \frac{p_e}{p_{ref}}\right)

where:

· $k = 0.35$ (dimensionless, calibrated to Langley data)
· $A_{ref} = \pi r_{nozzle}^2$ is nozzle exit area
· $p_{strength}$ is soil bearing strength (Pa)
· $t_{ref} = 1$ s is reference time
· $p_{ref} = 10^4$ Pa is reference pressure

For Starship at hover (100 m altitude, 10 seconds, $T = 2.3 \times 10^6$ N, $r_{nozzle} = 1.3$ m, $A_{ref} = 5.31$ m², $p_e = 5000$ Pa):

\frac{T/A_{ref}}{p_{strength}} = \frac{2.3 \times 10^6 / 5.31}{10^4} = \frac{433,000}{10,000} = 43.3

h_{crater} = 0.35 \times (43.3)^{0.45} \times (10)^{0.6} \times \left(1 + \frac{5000}{10000}\right)

(43.3)^{0.45} = e^{0.45 \ln(43.3)} = e^{0.45 \times 3.768} = e^{1.696} = 5.45

(10)^{0.6} = 10^{0.6} = 3.98

h_{crater} = 0.35 \times 5.45 \times 3.98 \times 1.5 = 0.35 \times 32.5 = 11.4 \text{ m}

This is larger than the 7.8 m in Chapter 6.7.1 because that calculation used a different reference area assumption. We use the consistent formulation throughout.

6.7.3 Ejecta Model

Ejecta velocity and range follow:

v_{ejecta}(r) = v_{max} \left( \frac{r}{r_0} \right)^{-1.5} \exp\left(-\frac{r}{r_{plume}}\right)

where:

· $v_{max} \approx 25$ m/s is maximum ejecta velocity
· $r_0 = 1$ m is reference radius
· $r_{plume} = 10$ m is plume scale length

The mass flux of ejecta is:

\dot{m}_{ejecta}(r) = \dot{m}_{total} \cdot f(r)

where $f(r)$ is normalized distribution.

Hazard criteria:

· Particles with $v > 10$ m/s can damage thermal protection
· Particles with $v > 5$ m/s can damage windows and sensors
· Particle flux > 1 kg/m²/s causes obscuration

6.7.4 PSI Implementation in Simulation

The PSI model is implemented as follows:

1. At each time step during terminal descent (altitude < 500 m), compute:
   · Instantaneous crater depth growth rate
   · Cumulative crater depth
   · Ejecta flux at vehicle location
2. Failure conditions:
   · Crater depth > landing gear height + 0.5 m (gear stroke)
   · Ejecta flux > critical value for damage
   · Obscuration > threshold for sensor dropout
3. Feedback on dynamics:
   · Crater modifies terrain elevation beneath vehicle
   · Ejecta impingement adds disturbance forces/torques

