6.8 Global Sensitivity Analysis (Sobol Indices)

6.8.1 Sobol Method Overview

Sobol sensitivity analysis decomposes the variance of an output quantity $Y$ into contributions from input parameters $X_i$:

V(Y) = \sum_i V_i + \sum_{i<j} V_{ij} + ... + V_{12...k}

where:

· $V_i = V(E[Y|X_i])$ is first-order effect
· $V_{ij} = V(E[Y|X_i, X_j]) - V_i - V_j$ is second-order interaction

The Sobol indices are:

S_i = \frac{V_i}{V(Y)} \quad \text{(first-order)}

S_{Ti} = S_i + \sum_{j\neq i} S_{ij} + ... \quad \text{(total-order)}

6.8.2 Implementation

Sobol indices are computed using the Saltelli sampling method with $N = 10,000$ samples per parameter (total runs: $N \times (2k+2) = 10,000 \times 28 = 280,000$ for $k=13$ parameters).

Algorithm 6.5: Sobol Index Computation

```
1. Generate two independent sample matrices A and B of size N×k
2. For each parameter i, create matrix C_i where column i comes from B, others from A
3. Evaluate model for all samples: Y_A, Y_B, Y_{C_i}
4. Compute:
   V(Y) = variance of [Y_A; Y_B]
   V_i = (1/N) Σ Y_A Y_{C_i} - (E[Y])^2
   V_{Ti} = (1/2N) Σ (Y_A - Y_{C_i})^2
5. S_i = V_i / V(Y)
   S_{Ti} = V_{Ti} / V(Y)
```

