Launch & Ascent (Orion) 0.990 SLS failure, abort system
Earth orbit operations 0.995 Rendezvous, docking
Refueling campaign 0.985 Transfer failure, boil-off excess
NRHO transit 0.995 Propulsion, navigation
NRHO operations 0.995 Docking, crew transfer
Descent & Landing 0.960 PSI, guidance, engines
Surface operations 0.995 EVA, life support
Ascent 0.985 Ascent engine, rendezvous
NRHO return 0.995 Docking, crew transfer
Earth return 0.990 Re-entry, landing

Assuming independence, the product gives:

P_{LOC} = 1 - \prod_{i=1}^{10} R_i = 1 - (0.99 \times 0.995^6 \times 0.985^2 \times 0.96)

= 1 - (0.99 \times 0.970 \times 0.970 \times 0.96) = 1 - 0.894 = 0.106

Thus 10.6% P_LOC under independence assumption.

7.6.2 Common-Cause Failure Adjustment

Independence is unrealistic. Common-cause failures (e.g., software error affecting multiple phases) increase P_LOC. Using the β-factor model from Section 5.6:

P_{LOC} = 1 - \prod_{i=1}^{n} (1 - P_{fail,i}) + \beta \cdot \max(P_{fail,i})

With $\beta = 0.2$ (typical for human spaceflight):

P_{LOC} = 0.106 + 0.2 \times 0.04 = 0.106 + 0.008 = 0.114

With $\beta = 0.3$ (conservative):

P_{LOC} = 0.106 + 0.3 \times 0.04 = 0.106 + 0.012 = 0.118

7.6.3 Comparison with Requirements

NASA's human-rating requirements (NPR 8705.2B) specify:

· P_LOC < 0.001 for ascent/entry phases
· P_LOC < 0.01 for overall mission (interpreted differently by programs)

The Artemis IV P_LOC of 11.4-11.8% far exceeds these thresholds. This is not surprising—first flights of new human spacecraft always have high risk. The Space Shuttle had estimated P_LOC ~1% after 100 flights, but first flights were much higher.

Historical context:

· Apollo 11: Estimated P_LOC ~5-10% pre-flight
· Space Shuttle (STS-1): Estimated P_LOC ~5-10%
· Commercial crew (Demo-2): Estimated P_LOC ~1-2%

Artemis IV's 11.4% is within the range of historical first-flight risks.

