   · All combined: +10.7%

8.2 Evidence-Based Recommendations

The following recommendations are prioritized based on their impact on mission success probability and feasibility of implementation before Artemis IV (early 2028).

8.2.1 Engine Development

Recommendation 1: Tighten thrust variation specification to ±1%

· Rationale: Thrust variation contributes 42% of landing error variance (Sobol $S_i = 0.42$). Reducing from ±2% to ±1% improves landing accuracy by approximately 2.2 m and success probability by 2.5%.
· Implementation: Enhance manufacturing tolerances, improve throttle control algorithms, and conduct extended test campaigns with 50+ engines to characterize statistical distribution.
· Timeline: 12-18 months; feasible for 2028 if initiated immediately.

Recommendation 2: Demonstrate deep throttle capability with single-engine hover

· Rationale: Starship's current 40% minimum throttle requires engine shutdown for hover, increasing complexity. Blue Moon's 10% throttle enables simpler operations.
· Implementation: Develop Raptor 3+ with 30% minimum throttle; validate in vacuum chamber tests.
· Timeline: 24 months; may not be ready for Artemis IV, so alternative (engine shutdown) must suffice.

8.2.2 PSI Mitigation (Starship)

Recommendation 3: Extend landing gear to 5-6 m

· Rationale: 95th percentile crater depth is 11.8 m; 3 m gear is inadequate. Even 6 m gear leaves 23% of runs exceeding gear height, but combined with other mitigations reduces failure to acceptable level.
· Implementation: Redesign landing gear struts, reinforce attachment points, conduct drop tests with 6 m stroke.
· Timeline: 18 months; critical path for Starship.

Recommendation 4: Implement engine shutdown at 10-15 m altitude

· Rationale: Eliminates plume impingement during final descent, reducing crater growth by 60% (from 7.8 m to 3.1 m for 10 s hover).
· Implementation: Modify guidance algorithm to include terminal phase with engines off; add RCS for attitude control during free-fall; validate with drop tests.
· Timeline: 12 months.

Recommendation 5: Elevate engine clusters

· Rationale: Each additional meter of engine height provides 2 seconds of safe operation before crater reaches gear.
· Implementation: Redesign thrust structure to position engines higher relative to landing gear; may require vehicle configuration changes.
· Timeline: 24 months; may slip to Artemis V.

Recommendation 6: Conduct robotic precursor pad preparation

· Rationale: Compacting soil increases bearing strength, reducing crater depth by 27% for factor-of-2 increase.
· Implementation: CLPS mission with compaction system (e.g., roller, vibratory compactor) to prepare 30 m diameter pad at Shackleton rim.
· Timeline: 24 months; requires dedicated CLPS mission in 2027.

8.2.3 Landing Site Selection

Recommendation 7: Require 150 m diameter safe zone

· Rationale: PSI-induced ejecta and cratering enlarge effective hazard zone. Monte Carlo shows 27.8 m 3σ ellipse expands to effective radius of ~75 m when PSI failures included.
· Implementation: Survey candidate sites with Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter (LRO) and CLPS missions to identify 150 m clear area with <16° slope.
· Timeline: Ongoing; should be complete by 2027.

Recommendation 8: Avoid volatile-rich PSRs for first landing

· Rationale: Volatile outgassing could obscure sensors and alter soil properties unpredictably.
· Implementation: Select site on Shackleton rim, not interior, with <5% PSR fraction within 500 m.
· Timeline: Immediate.

8.2.4 Refueling Campaign

Recommendation 9: Implement optimized 9-tanker clustered schedule with active cooling backup

· Rationale: MILP optimization shows 9 tankers with clustered launches achieve -0.6% margin without active cooling, +1.2% with active cooling. Adding 10th tanker provides 10.6% margin.
· Implementation:
  · Launch tankers in final 10 days before departure
  · Include active cooling on at least 3 tankers to enable 9-tanker solution
  · Have 10th tanker on standby for launch if boil-off exceeds 1.2%/day
· Timeline: Operational for 2028.

Recommendation 10: Demonstrate full refueling sequence on Artemis III

· Rationale: Bayesian updating shows successful Artemis III refueling improves posterior success by 2.5%.
· Implementation: Artemis III mission in 2027 should include:
  · 3-4 tanker launches
  · Complete propellant transfer to HLS in LEO
  · Measurement of transfer efficiency and boil-off rates
· Timeline: 2027.

8.2.5 Trajectory Design

Recommendation 11: Fly fuel-optimal SOCP trajectories with PSI penalty

· Rationale: Unified optimization with PSI penalty reduces crater depth from 7.8 m to 6.2 m while saving one tanker flight.
· Implementation: Implement SOCP guidance in flight software with real-time updates; include penalty term $\lambda \cdot h_{crater}$ in objective.
· Timeline: 12 months for software development and testing.

Recommendation 12: Minimize hover time below 100 m

· Rationale: Crater depth scales as $t_{burn}^{0.6}$; reducing hover from 30 s to 15 s reduces crater depth by factor $(0.5)^{0.6} = 0.66$.
· Implementation: Optimize hazard detection to complete within 10 s; use faster scanning LiDAR; pre-select multiple safe sites.
· Timeline: 12 months.

8.2.6 Precursor Missions

Recommendation 13: Conduct uncrewed Starship south-pole landing before Artemis IV

· Rationale: Each successful uncrewed landing reduces posterior P_LOC by 2-3%. Three landings bring P_LOC from 11.4% to 5.6%.
· Implementation: Schedule Starship uncrewed demo in 2027, with full PSI instrumentation (cameras, erosion sensors, ejecta detectors).
· Timeline: 2027.

Recommendation 14: CLPS mission with PSI instrumentation

· Rationale: Direct measurement of plume effects at smaller scale validates scaling laws.
· Implementation: Add PSI sensor package (erosion probes, accelerometers, cameras) to 2027 CLPS lander.
· Timeline: 2027.

Recommendation 15: Orbital refueling demonstration with 10 tankers

· Rationale: Validates logistics of large-scale refueling campaign.
· Implementation: Conduct 10-tanker campaign in 2026-2027, separate from Artemis III, to prove concept.
· Timeline: 2026-2027.

8.2.7 Abort Thresholds

Recommendation 16: Establish real-time abort decision criteria

Based on simulation results, abort if:

Condition Threshold Rationale
Posterior success probability <92% Below acceptable risk
PSI crater projection 5 m at 100 m altitude Exceeds gear height with margin
Hazard detection <3 safe sites within 150 m Insufficient landing options
Fuel margin <3% at powered descent initiation Insufficient reserves
Engine-out Loss of >1 engine (Starship) or engine failure (Blue Moon) Insufficient thrust

· Implementation: Integrate real-time Bayesian updates into mission control displays; train flight controllers on abort criteria.
· Timeline: 12 months.

8.2.8 Human-Rating Pathway

Recommendation 17: Require 3-5 successful uncrewed landings before crew certification

· Rationale: Bayesian analysis shows P_LOC reduces from 11.4% to 4.0% after 5 successful landings.
· Implementation: Schedule:
  · 2026: Uncrewed demo 1 (orbital refueling only)
  · 2027: Uncrewed demo 2 (south pole landing)
  · 2027: Uncrewed demo 3 (south pole landing)
  · 2028: Artemis IV (crewed) after 3 successes
  · 2028: Artemis V (second crewed) if warranted
· Timeline: 2026-2028.

8.2.9 Vehicle Selection

Recommendation 18: Use Blue Moon for Artemis IV, Starship for Artemis V+

· Rationale: Blue Moon offers 96.1% mitigated success probability with 20 t cargo—sufficient for first landing with essential science. Starship's higher risk (93.8%) but greater cargo capacity (50 t @ 95% success) is better suited for later missions after PSI mitigations validated.
· Implementation:
  · Artemis IV: Blue Moon with 20 t cargo (habitat module, science package)
  · Artemis V: Starship with 50 t cargo (rovers, ISRU plant)
· Timeline: Immediate decision needed for Artemis IV HLS final selection.

8.2.10 Programmatic Recommendations

Recommendation 19: Maintain dual-provider strategy

· Rationale: Starship and Blue Moon offer complementary capabilities. Losing either reduces flexibility and increases programmatic risk.
· Implementation: Continue funding both HLS contracts through Artemis V; downselect only after 3+ successful landings by each.

Recommendation 20: Increase flight cadence to 2 per year by 2029

· Rationale: The February 2026 restructuring emphasized "muscle memory." High cadence maintains operational proficiency and enables rapid learning.
· Implementation: Secure budget for 2 SLS/Orion launches per year starting 2029; preposition HLS vehicles at Gateway.

8.3 Implications for Future Exploration

8.3.1 Mars Forward

The technologies and operational concepts validated on Artemis IV directly enable Mars exploration:

1. Orbital refueling: Required for Mars transfer vehicles; Artemis demonstrates at lunar scale.
2. Cryogenic fluid management: Boil-off control for Mars transit (6-8 months) builds on lunar experience (weeks).
3. Precision landing: Mars requires 100 m accuracy for site safety; lunar south pole landing demonstrates comparable capability.
4. PSI mitigation: Mars landers will face similar plume interaction with regolith; lunar data validates models.
5. Adaptive control: NCE algorithms developed for lunar landing apply directly to Mars entry, descent, and landing.

8.3.2 Sustainable Lunar Presence

Artemis IV is not an endpoint but the beginning of sustained lunar presence:

· Artemis V-VIII: Build lunar base at Shackleton rim
· ISRU demonstration: Extract water ice, produce propellant
· Long-duration stays: 30-180 days
· International collaboration: ESA, JAXA, CSA modules

The mathematical frameworks developed in this dissertation—particularly the unified optimization and Bayesian risk updating—provide tools for continuously improving safety as experience accumulates.

8.4 Closing Remarks

The February 27, 2026 restructuring of the Artemis campaign was a recognition of a fundamental truth: returning humans to the Moon after five decades is harder than it looks. The Apollo program succeeded through monolithic engineering and acceptable risk for its era. Artemis must succeed through rigorous analysis, probabilistic risk assessment, and evidence-based decision-making.

This dissertation has provided that analysis. The mathematics are clear: PSI is the dominant risk driver for Starship, thrust variation is the critical control parameter, and refueling efficiency determines margin. The simulations are quantitative: 93.8% success probability for Starship with mitigations, 96.1% for Blue Moon. The recommendations are actionable: extend landing gear, tighten engine specifications, conduct precursor missions, and fly Blue Moon first.

The path forward is challenging but clear. With the mitigations recommended here, Artemis IV can succeed. With the precursor campaign proposed, Artemis V and beyond will be safer. And with the mathematical frameworks developed, future explorers will have the tools they need to venture further—to Mars and beyond.

The Moon awaits. And this time, we will stay.

